snippet.textDisplay: Cerrone threw the fight! Proof: the way Conor and Cerrone acted leading up to the fight, no tension, jovial with each other, very unlike Conor. The fact that Masvidal was at the fight talking about a fight with Conor. The betting odds were way in favor of Conor, even though Cerrone would be one of Connor's toughest opponents, considering his size and skillset - Vegas won a TON of money because a lot of people bet on Cerrone. The match looked rehearsed. Yes the punches and kicks were real, but these guys do this for a living. The way Conor won it seemed like he was the bigger, stronger, more skilled fighter.. this couldn't be further from the truth. Cerrone hot hit and went down. This was the only way to make it look real, rehearse a sequence and end it quickly because the longer the fight the more it would have looked fixed. When has Cerrone been dominated this quickly by anybody, and we're supposed to believe Conor is this freak athlete now? The fact is, Conor couldn't lose, because that would be the end of UFC's cash cow. So the UFC called on the one guy they could count on to take the fall, and a giant payday. Everyone got taken for a ride...UFC IS THE NEW WWE.

snippet.textDisplay: Cerrone did the same thing in every fight where he got pressured and hit early. He turtles up, gets his hands to his face, bends his back and turns away. What reason was there to believe he wouldn't do that yesterday? It went exactly the way most people predicted. You can't take away anything from Conor, he did his job. But it doesn't prove that he's superman once again. Don't get me wrong, I love Cerrone, but he just seems to give up and accept the loss when he gets hit early. He's coming to the point where the UFC will put him in against youngsters who can shine up their records by beating the once great Cowboy. He hardly got hit yesterday and his face was busted up like he was hit by a train. Look at his last couple of fights (he looks like the elephant man after the fight each time), he can't handle the damage like he once could. It's one thing accepting every fight, but once you start accepting fights not caring whether you win or not, it's time to stop and think about your health.
